On Bacon's vague and improper use ol the word ‘motion,’ see the first note on this Aphorism. Here it cannot be rendered even by ‘process' or ‘operation,’ hut we must reson to some word of very wide meaning, such as ‘tendeney' or ‘affection' of matter.

‘laertia’ the property of which Bacon here speaks, is simply the inca· pacity ol matter to change its own state oi rest or motion. The obscure notions oi Bacon and his contemporaries about motion prevented them from seeing that this property applies as much to the tendency oi a body in motion to go on moving as to that of a body at rest to remain at rest. For a briel account oi the establishment of the F irst Law oi Motion (which seems to have been first enunciated by Galileo in 1638), see Whewell's History oi the Inductive Sciences, vol. ii. bk. vi. ch. 2.
